–Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1212":"1212","1130":"1130","about 1135":"about 1135","1150":"1150","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Staveley, Derbyshire, England":"Staveley, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Musard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Durham): nickname or occupational name from Middle English <i>mustard</i> ‘mustard’ (Old French <i>mostarde</i>). The allusion could perhaps be to someone with a sharp tongue, but is probably usually to a dealer in mustard."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":80,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":89,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Musard was born about 1135, in Staveley, Derbyshire, England. She had at least 1 son with William de Withington."},"et":{"about 1135–":"umbes 1135–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1150–1212":"1150–1212","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1212":"1212","1130":"1130","about 1135":"umbes 1135","1150":"1150","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Staveley, Derbyshire, England":"Staveley, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1135–":"noin 1135–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1150–1212":"1150–1212","1135–Female":"1135–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1212":"1212","1130":"1130","about 1135":"noin 1135","1150":"1150","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Staveley, Derbyshire, England":"Staveley, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1135–":"environ 1135–Décédée","1130–Male":"1130–Décédé","1150–1212":"1150–1212","1135–Female":"1135–Décédée","about 1150":"environ 1150","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1212